[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Introduction "]
[Result "*"]

{ Hey everyone! This is GM Eugene Perelshteyn, and thank you for buying my course, the Hyper Accelerated Dragon Lifetime Repertoire.   Some of you may already know me as a Chessable author from my previous course: The Grand Prix Attack; others may have some of my books, actually!   In this course, I'll be sharing my favorite opening that I played all of my life in one version or another.  I fell in love with this opening as a kid but over the years as I got stronger, I've learned that the Dragon is a little bit risky. Then its friend, the Accelerated Dragon was able to replace it but it had its own move order problems, so for this course, I'll be recommending the Hyper Accelerated Dragon! An entire repertoire based on the Sicilian Defense after 1.e4. }
1. e4 c5
{ Since this is a Lifetime Repertoire, I'll be looking at every single possibility that your opponent can throw at you as early as move two! }
2. Nf3
{ White enters the main line.   Please note that in this course I hold nothing back! For example against the Smith-Morra  2.d4  cxd4  3.c3  in the past I've recommended sidestepping this gambit for the sake of time with the move  3...g6  but since you all have Chessable now and the MoveTrainer we're going for what I believe is the refutation  3...dxc3  which should be easy to learn now thanks to the MoveTrainer! }
2... g6
{ This is the Hyper-Accelerated Dragon move order. Black's idea is to fianchetto the bishop on g7 first, controlling the long diagonal.   Please note that we avoid  2...Nc6  as it allows  3.Bb5  which is known as the Rossolimo Variation, which leads to totally different types of positions. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4
{ The main point of my course is to sidestep the annoying Maroczy Bind  @@StartBracket@@  4...Nc6  5.c4  @@EndBracket@@. I believe this is the only setup that can seriously take the fun away from our beloved Accelerated Dragon.  So, you may wonder how this is possible. Well, two important discoveries got me excited to rekindle the Dragon fire and share my analysis with you. They both start with an unusual move: }
4... Nf6
{ This is my recommended way to play this opening as by attacking the e4-pawn, we sidestep the Maroczy Bind  4...Nc6  4.c4  .   5.e5  is a straight up blunder because of  5...Qa5  picking up the pawn.   If you play  4...Nc6  we transpose into the Accelerated Dragon but it is not our recommendation for this course to avoid the really annoying  5.c4  here! }
5. Nc3 { Now I will show two ways of playing this position! } 5... Nc6
{ This move order is my personal discovery. We still would like to transpose into the Accelerated Dragon after a natural  6.Be3  Bg7  . The only drawback is now White can take on c6 leading into the endgame. Please note that in this position, White can never castle queenside. If they continue with the typical plan of  7.f3  O-O  8.Qd2  is met by the beautiful pawn thrust  8...d5!  which is the entire point of this opening with very tactical play where I've personally won many games!  White can also play @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pp1pppbp/2n2np1/8/3NP3/2N1B3/PPP2PPP/R2QKB1R w KQkq - 5 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Bc4  where I recommend  7...Qa5  even though nothing is wrong with  7...O-O  I believe that putting pressure on the e4 pawn first is the better way of playing this position where we get our typical Sicilian play with our e and d pawns vs. White's lonely  e4  pawn.   The sharp Dragondorf  5...d6  is our alternative,  6.Be3  Bg7  7.f3  a6  the Najdorf move.  8.Qd2  h5!  Welcome to the Dragondorf, the fighting cousin of the Hyper-Accelerated Dragon @@StartBracket@@HAD@@EndBracket@@ and my most fighting weapon as Black!  The main point is that Black's last move ...h5 takes away White's main idea of g4, h4, and h5 with a simple attack. Moreover, he can't trade the bishops with Bh6.  White is now left dazed and confused without a clear plan. Black, however, is ready to swing with the Dragon's tail ...b5 and launch a powerful attack.  I believe the Dragondorf was always considered a slightly dubious opening, and no one had written any serious books on it. This is good news for us! After studying the lines carefully, you would be armed with strong ideas against an unprepared opponent. I would not be surprised if you got powerful attacks after studying my course! Please don't forget to share them with me on the Discussion board! }
6. Nxc6 { The main drawback of our move order. } 6... dxc6 7. Qxd8+ Kxd8
{ I call this endgame the safer approach, compared to the Dragondorf. Black loses the right to castle but preserves a great pawn structure.  As a matter of fact, I believe that his c6-pawn, restricting the knight on c3, gives Black long-term chances. I am happy to share my fresh ideas with you.  Similarly, to the Dragondorf, your opponent will be totally unprepared for this endgame! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
