[Black "Smith-Morra Gambit #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. d4 cxd4 3. c3 dxc3
{ In the past I have recommended a simple move  3...g6  to sidestep the Smith-Morra. While it's a good surprise weapon, in this course I have decided to focus on the refutation instead. }
4. Nxc3 Nc6 5. Nf3 e6 6. Bc4 { This is by far the most popular move. } 6... Bb4
{ I recommend this simple setup. It's quite rare with just over 600 games in the database @@StartBracket@@compared to almost 3000 games with ...a6@@EndBracket@@. }
7. O-O
{ 7.Bd2  Nge7  8.O-O  d5  9.exd5  exd5⩱  .   7.Bf4  transposes to 6.Bf4. } 7...
Nge7
{ Black is ready to castle or to strike with ...d5 at the right moment. We will cover all of the popular tries by White. }
8. Qe2 { The main try for White. } 8... O-O 9. Rd1 Ng6
{ Thematic idea. Black wants to meet  10.Bg5  with  10...Be7  . } 10. Bg5
{ 10.Be3  Bxc3  11.bxc3  b6⩱  followed by Bb7 with a slight edge for Black. }
10... Be7 11. Bxe7 Qxe7
{ Black's position is rock solid and they just need to develop the bishop now. }
12. e5 f6
{ Removing the pawn from the center and clearing the way for the e- and d-pawns. }
13. exf6 gxf6 14. Rac1 d5 { 15.Bd3  Nf4∓  . } 15. Bb3 Kh8
{ Black tucks away the king from the x-ray of the b3-bishop and stands clearly better. We should next finish development with ...Bd7 and dominate the game with the extra pawn and the mobile center. }
