[Black "2.g3 without Nc3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. g3
{ This is a somewhat tricky system, White is playing the Closed Sicilian with the knight on b1. The point is that they may try c3 & d4 later to take over the center. }
2... g6 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. Ne2
{ 4.Nc3  Nc6  transposes to Closed Sicilian covered here. } 4... Nc6 5. O-O d6
6. c3
{ White aims to play d4 and take over the center. Therefore we must stop it at once! }
6... e5
{ This is the key move that stops White's main idea. The only drawback is the weakness of d5. However, as you will see it would take White too long to reroute the knight there, while Black will generate rapid counterplay. }
7. Na3 Nge7 8. Nc2 { White is trying to be clever and still play for d4 } 8...
d5
{ This is the key move that now requires White to be precise as the passive  9.d3?!  will get them in trouble. }
9. exd5 Nxd5 10. d4 { Now the game simplifies } 10... cxd4 11. cxd4 exd4 12.
Nexd4 O-O { We don't mind the weakening of our pawn structure, after } 13. Nxc6
bxc6 14. Nd4 Bd7
{ Black is actually slightly better due to the pressure along the b-file. For example: }
15. Re1 Qb6 16. Nb3 Rae8
{ Black's pieces are fully developed with lots of pressure, while White is having a hard time developing the queenside. }
