[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "Closed Sicilian: 2.Nc3 3.g3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 g6 3. g3 Bg7 4. Bg2 Nc6 5. d3 d6
{ We've reached a classic Closed Sicilian pawn structure. Notice how the pawn chains will determine the plans for both sides. White's pawn chain of c2-d3-e4 dictates that he should play for the kingside attack with a future f4-f5 plan. Black, on the other hand, will prepare the tail swing with a future b5-b4. }
6. Be3
{ White's most popular and flexible choice. He could start the attack with Qd2 or develop naturally with Nge2 next. }
6... Nf6 { Black develops naturally and wants to meet Qd2 with ...Ng4! } 7. h3
O-O 8. Qd2 Nd4
{ Black takes over the key outpost, making it harder for White to play Bh6 as c2 pawn will hang. }
9. Nd1 { White's idea is to drive the knight away from d4 with 10.c3 } 9... e5
{ An important move! Black anticipates c3 and shores up the center. } 10. c3
Ne6
{ By protecting c5-pawn Black is getting ready to strike in the center with ...d5! }
11. f4 exf4 12. gxf4 d5
{ Black blows open the center and happily sacs the c5 pawn. See model game: Al Awadhi,W @@StartBracket@@2034@@EndBracket@@-Salem,A @@StartBracket@@2567@@EndBracket@@ Tagaytay City 2013. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "Grand Prix 2.Nc3 g6 3.f4 Bg7 4.Nf3 a6 "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nc3
{ I recommend this move in my White's course: Grand Prix Attack Reloaded. But, I will share with you a fresh way to avoid any attack! }
2... g6
{ We still choose our favorite move order, since  2...Nc6  invites  3.Bb5  . }
3. f4 Bg7 4. Nf3 a6
{ This rare move was only played in 137 games in my DB, compared to  4...Nc6  , which has over 3200 games!   Black immediately stops White's main idea of 5.Bb5 and also discourages  5.Bc4  due to  5...b5! }
5. a4
{ A useful waiting move. White is waiting for  5...Nc6  to play  6.Bc4  transposing to the Old Grand Prix lines with the inclusion of a4 & a6. }
5... e6
{ I recommend this rare move to counter Bc4 ideas. Black doesn't want to waste any time on ...Nc6 and instead goes for rapid kingside development with ... Nge7 & d5. }
6. e5
{ This is the only way to fight for advantage. This rare idea is recommended in my Grand Prix Reloaded course but without the inclusion of a4 & a6. It turns out that having the pawn on a6 is vital for Black and makes this idea playable since White won't have the option of future Nb5! }
6... d5
{ Black fights for the center right away. The game now enters a French Defense pawn structure where White wants to solidify the center with f4-e5-d4 triangle while Black is seeking active counter with ...f6 and queenside pressure. }
7. d4 Nc6 { A natural development move and also a novelty! } 8. Ne2
{ White stabilizes the d4-pawn, hoping to develop the f1-bishop on g2 or h3 in the future. }
8... Nge7 9. dxc5 { Here White can take the pawn, but after } 9... O-O 10. c3
f6 11. exf6 Bxf6 12. g3 b6
{ I believe Black has full compensation due to faster development. For example: }
13. Be3
{ Is best.   13.cxb6?!  Qxb6∓  Despite being a pawn down, Black is better as it's hard for White to develop the pieces. }
13... Nf5 14. Bf2 Rb8 { Black prepares a cool exchange sac idea } 15. cxb6 Rxb6
16. Bxb6 Qxb6
{ White's king is stuck in the center, and with the threats of ...Ne3 and ...Qxb2 Black has full compensation for the exchange and pawn! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "2.Nc3 & Bc4, d3 setup"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 g6 3. Bc4 Bg7 4. d3 Nc6 5. a3 d6
{ We're going for the standard Dragon setup.   5...e6  with idea 6...Nge7 & d5 are totally playable as well. }
6. Nge2
{ Here, Black has two equally good ways to develop: ...Nf6 or ...e6 & Nge7. Generally, I prefer to put the knight on f6 as it's more effective against White's h4-h5 plan. }
6... Nf6 7. h4
{ We've reached a blitz game Carlsen-Guseinov, 2017 via transposition. Black played a solid idea. }
7... h5
{ I like this simple approach and also recommend this move vs 3.h4.   7...e6Ν  is also quite strong, for example  8.h5?!  Nxh5  9.Rxh5?  gxh5  10.Nf4  h4-+  . }
8. Bg5 a6
{ 8...Nd4?!  this was played by Guseinov, which is a tempo loss as White wasn't threatening d4. }
9. Qd2
{ 9.d4?  cxd4  10.Nxd4  O-O⩱  We've reached a normal Dragon with a tempo up as White played d3 & d4. }
9... b5 10. Ba2 Bb7
{ Black continues with queenside development, waiting for White to commit the king. }
11. O-O Nh7 { Asking the bishop an important question. } 12. Bh6 Bxh6 13. Qxh6
e6
{ It turns out that h4 is weak and Black king can castle the other way, for example: }
14. g3 { 14.Qg7  Qf6  15.Qxf6  Nxf6  is a comfortable endgame for Black. }
14... Qe7 15. Qg7 { White's queen is getting into deep trouble! } 15... O-O-O
{ With a winning edge thanks to the awkward White queen on g7! } *

