1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 g6
{ This is the Hyper-Accelerated Dragon move order. Black's idea is to fianchetto the bishop on g7 first, controlling the long diagonal.   Please note that we avoid  2...Nc6  as it allows  3.Bb5  which is known as the Rossolimo Variation, which leads to totally different types of positions. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6
{ This is my recommended way to play this opening as by attacking the e4-pawn we sidestep the Maroczy Bind  4...Nc6  4.c4  . }
5. Nc3 d6
{ In this chapter, I will cover all the other setups for White, except for the 6.Be3, f3, Qd2 setup known as the Yugoslav Attack. }
6. Be2
{ This is known as the Classical variation. White just wants to castle and complete development. }
6... Bg7 7. O-O O-O
{ White has several plans here:  1@@EndBracket@@ Develop naturally with  8.Be3   2@@EndBracket@@ Play  8.Nb3  with idea of Re1, Bf1, Bg5 and a timely Nd5 jump Depending on what White does Black either strikes in the center or expands on the queenside with a6 & b5. }
8. Nb3
{ White removes the knight from d4 to take full control of the d5-outpost and prepares for the strategic fight. }
8... Nc6 9. Bg5 a6 { with a standard idea to expand with ...b5 next } 10. f4 b5
{ Both sides are executing their plans: White wants to establish the bishop on f3 while Black is planning to push ...b4 }
11. Bf3 b4 { Driving the knight towards d5 or away from the center } 12. Nd5
{ this natural move would actually lose a pawn after } 12... Nxd5 13. exd5 Na5
{ White is now facing major issues on the queenside: weak b2 pawn, knight jumping to c4, and intermezzo ...Qb6+. For example,  14.Rb1  Nc4  15.Qc1  a5∓  with strong play on the queenside.   14.Re1  Nxb3!  15.axb3  Bxb2  16.Bxe7  Qb6+  17.Kh1  Re8!  18.Rb1  Bc3  19.Re2  Bd7∓  with a threat of ...Bb5 Black will take over the game. Surprisingly, the engines already give -2 here! }
