1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 g6
{ This is the Hyper-Accelerated Dragon move order. Black's idea is to fianchetto the bishop on g7 first, controlling the long diagonal.   Please note that we avoid  2...Nc6  as it allows  3.Bb5  which is known as the Rossolimo Variation, which leads to totally different types of positions. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6
{ This is my recommended way to play this opening as by attacking the e4-pawn we sidestep the Maroczy Bind  4...Nc6  4.c4  . }
5. Nc3 Nc6 6. Nxc6 dxc6
{ Black invites the endgame but loses the right to castle!   6...bxc6?!  this is not as good here as with the bishops on g7 & e3. After  7.e5  Black's best try is  7...Nh5!   @@StartBracket@@  7...Ng8  8.Bc4  Bg7  9.Qf3±  with a big attack, as Black is lagging in development.@@EndBracket@@  8.Bc4  Qa5  9.O-O!  Qxe5  10.Re1±  with a big initiative for the pawn. }
7. Qxd8+ Kxd8
{ I believe this endgame is completely playable for Black as it's not easy for White to take advantage of the uncastled king. The pawn structure is somewhat symmetrical, and if Black is able to play ...e5 and develop, we may even be slightly better.   Please note that White's knight is restricted by the c6-pawn, making it difficult to generate active play. }
8. Bf4 { White gets ready to castle with check next } 8... Be6
{ I like this unusual idea to stop Bc4 } 9. O-O-O+ Ke8 10. Be2
{ 10.f3  h5  Ν with the same ideas as in 10.Be2. } 10... h5
{ A nice novelty with a simple idea of ...Bh6. Please note that once Black trades the dark-squared bishops and expands with ...h4 and ...g5 followed by ...Nd7-e5, he would be better! For example: }
11. Kb1 Bh6 12. Bxh6 Rxh6 13. Rd2 h4 14. h3 g5 15. Rhd1 Nd7 16. f3 Ne5
{ With a dream setup for Black. } *

