3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6
{ This is my recommended way to play this opening as by attacking the e4-pawn we sidestep the Maroczy Bind  4...Nc6  4.c4  . }
5. Nc3 Nc6 6. Be3
{ With this move we transpose into the main Accelerated Dragon setup! } 6...
Bg7 7. Bc4 { This is the main line. } 7... Qa5
{ I prefer this simple move to force White to castle short. However,  7...O-O  is totally fine and was my recommendation back in 2005 in Chess Openings Explained for Black. }
8. O-O O-O
{ White has two plans here:  A@@EndBracket@@  9.Bb3  with idea to use the d5-outpost in the future  B@@EndBracket@@  9.Nb3  to gain a tempo on the queen and retreat the bishop to e2. }
9. Bb3 { This the most popular setup at GM level. } 9... d6
{ With this move we've transposed to a normal Dragon. The only difference is having the queen on a5, which is not that bad. Due to the ...Ng4 threat White typically reacts with  10.h3  or  10.f3  . }
10. f3 Bd7 11. Qd2 Rfe8
{ I played this rare move at Chicago Open in 2008 vs a young talent, Daggapati Balaji, who became a GM in 2022. }
12. Rfd1 Rac8 13. Rac1 Ne5
{ Black's plan is to expand on the queenside with ...a6 & ...b5 while constantly threatening ...Nc4. I won a nice model game: Daggapati,B @@StartBracket@@2324@@EndBracket@@ -Perelshteyn,E @@StartBracket@@2605@@EndBracket@@ Chicago Open 2018. }
