[White "3) Non-Dangerous Dragons [Alternative]"]
[Black "4.Nxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 d6 6.g3 Bg7 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 g6
{ This is the Hyper-Accelerated Dragon move order. Black's idea is to fianchetto the bishop on g7 first, controlling the long diagonal.   Please note that we avoid  2...Nc6  as it allows  3.Bb5  which is known as the Rossolimo Variation, which leads to totally different types of positions. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6
{ This is my recommended way to play this opening as by attacking the e4-pawn we sidestep the Maroczy Bind  4...Nc6  4.c4  . }
5. Nc3 d6
{ In this chapter, I will cover all the other setups for White, except for the 6.Be3, f3, Qd2 setup known as the Yugoslav Attack. }
6. g3
{ White goes for a slow fianchetto setup that allows Black plenty of time to develop comfortably. }
6... Bg7 7. Bg2 O-O 8. O-O Nc6 9. Nxc6 bxc6 10. e5
{ This is a tempting idea to ruin Black's structure but Black is totally fine after: }
10... dxe5 11. Qxd8 Rxd8 12. Bxc6 Rb8
{ The control of the d and b-files and better development gives Black good play. For example: }
13. Re1 Bf5 14. Rxe5 { 14.Ba4  Nd7=  . } 14... e6 15. Ra5 Ng4 16. Rxa7 Bd4
{ And Black eventually won in the online game Teclaf, P  @@StartBracket@@2543@@EndBracket@@-Keymer, V @@StartBracket@@2607@@EndBracket@@ chess24.com INT 2021. }
