[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3) Non-Dangerous Dragons [Alternative]"]
[Black "4.Nxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 d6 6.f4 Bg7 "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 g6
{ This is the Hyper-Accelerated Dragon move order. Black's idea is to fianchetto the bishop on g7 first, controlling the long diagonal.   Please note that we avoid  2...Nc6  as it allows  3.Bb5  which is known as the Rossolimo Variation, which leads to totally different types of positions. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6
{ This is my recommended way to play this opening as by attacking the e4-pawn we sidestep the Maroczy Bind  4...Nc6  4.c4  . }
5. Nc3 d6
{ In this chapter, I will cover all the other setups for White, except for the 6.Be3, f3, Qd2 setup known as the Yugoslav Attack. }
6. f4
{ This is a rare but dangerous move known as the Levenfish Variation. Black has to react accurately. }
6... Nc6
{ The most accurate move order.   6...Bg7?!  Allows White's main idea.  7.e5  dxe5  8.fxe5   @@StartBracket@@And now Black can lose the game after the natural:  8...Ng4?  9.Bb5+  Kf8  10.Ne6++-  oops! @@EndBracket@@  8...Nfd7  9.e6⩲  this is still bad for Black, but at least it's not losing. }
7. Nxc6 bxc6 8. e5 Nd7
{ This is a must-know move! Black forces White to trade on d6 and pretty much solves all his opening problems. }
9. exd6 exd6 10. Be3 Be7
{ Notice that it's important to develop the bishop on e7 as d6 pawn needs to be guarded.   10...Nf6⩱  followed by ...Bg7 next. }
11. Qd2 O-O 12. O-O-O d5
{ Here we can see that Black's strong center together with half-open b-file will give us nice counterplay. Let know show you a cool line if White tries a direct attack with g4: }
13. g4 Re8 { A mysterious rook move that sets a deadly tactic! } 14. f5
{ 14.g5  Bb4  15.h4  Nc5  16.h5  Qe7  17.Bd4  Ne4∓  with a big edge for Black. }
14... d4 { A shocker! } 15. Qxd4 { 15.Bxd4  Bg5-+  wins the queen. } 15... Bf6
{ First this intermezzo move to open up our rook. } 16. Qd2 Rxe3 { Bam! } 17.
Qxe3 Bg5 { And White loses the queen due to the deadly skewer. } *

