{ This is the Hyper-Accelerated Dragon move order. Black's idea is to fianchetto the bishop on g7 first, controlling the long diagonal.   Please note that we avoid  2...Nc6  as it allows  3.Bb5  which is known as the Rossolimo Variation, which leads to totally different types of positions. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6
{ This is my recommended way to play this opening as by attacking the e4-pawn we sidestep the Maroczy Bind  4...Nc6  4.c4  . }
5. Nc3 d6
{ In this chapter, I will cover all the other setups for White, except for the 6.Be3, f3, Qd2 setup known as the Yugoslav Attack. }
6. Be2
{ This is known as the Classical variation. White just wants to castle and complete development. }
6... Bg7 7. Be3 { White keeps the option of castling long. } 7... O-O
{ Here we're not afraid of the Yugoslav Attack with Qd2, O-O-O as Be2 gives up a key tempo!   Now  8.O-O  Transposes to the 7.O-O line. }
8. Qd2 Nc6 9. f3 d5
{ This is a thematic idea from the Yugoslav Attack. The difference between Be2 vs O-O-O favors Black! }
10. Nxc6 bxc6 11. O-O-O { This allows Black a strong attack. } 11... Qc7
{ Inviting White to win the pawn to open up files. } 12. exd5 Nxd5 13. Nxd5
cxd5 14. Qxd5 Bf5
{ This is a dream attacking position for Black with c & b files and two bishops aiming at White's king! }
15. Qc5 Qb7 16. Qb5
{ A natural idea to seek trades runs into a tactical refutation: } 16... Rac8
17. Qxb7 Rxc2+ 18. Kb1 Rxb2+ 19. Kc1 { 19.Ka1  Rb1#  a beautiful mate! } 19...
Rc2+ 20. Kb1 Rxe2+ { The windmill theme forces White to give up the rook! } 21.
Rd3 Bxd3+ 22. Kc1 Rxe3 23. Kd2 Bh6
{ Rook and two bishops should win easily against White's exposed king. } *

