{ In this chapter, I will cover all the other setups for White, except for the 6.Be3, f3, Qd2 setup known as the Yugoslav Attack. }
6. Be2
{ This is known as the Classical variation. White just wants to castle and complete development. }
6... Bg7 7. O-O O-O
{ White has several plans here:  1@@EndBracket@@ Develop naturally with  8.Be3   2@@EndBracket@@ Play  8.Nb3  with idea of Re1, Bf1, Bg5 and a timely Nd5 jump Depending on what White does Black either strikes in the center or expands on the queenside with a6 & b5. }
8. Be3 Nc6 9. Qd2 d5
{ This thematic push is very common in many Dragon and Accelerated Dragon positions. The only drawback is that it often leads to many trades and equality.  However, Black has other moves that keep the game complex such as  9...Ng4  and  9...Bd7  . }
10. exd5 Nxd5 11. Nxc6 bxc6
{ Black's pawn structure is damaged, but the monster knight and g7 bishop provide plenty of counterplay. The game could continue: }
12. Rad1 Qc7 { Again, inviting White to win the pawn. } 13. Nxd5
{ 13.Bd4  e5!  14.Bc5  Rd8=  with strong central pressure. } 13... cxd5 14.
Qxd5
{ Now, the game peters out to equality with the following forced sequence: }
14... Be6 15. Qc5 Qxc5 16. Bxc5 Bxb2 17. Bxe7 Rfe8 18. Bc5 Bxa2
{ And all three games in the database finished in a draw here. } *

