{ This is the Hyper-Accelerated Dragon move order. Black's idea is to fianchetto the bishop on g7 first, controlling the long diagonal.   Please note that we avoid  2...Nc6  as it allows  3.Bb5  which is known as the Rossolimo Variation, which leads to totally different types of positions. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6
{ This is my recommended way to play this opening as by attacking the e4-pawn we sidestep the Maroczy Bind  4...Nc6  4.c4  . }
5. Nc3 d6
{ In this chapter, I will cover all the other setups for White, except for the 6.Be3, f3, Qd2 setup known as the Yugoslav Attack. }
6. Be2
{ This is known as the Classical variation. White just wants to castle and complete development. }
6... Bg7 7. O-O O-O
{ White has several plans here:  1@@EndBracket@@ Develop naturally with  8.Be3   2@@EndBracket@@ Play  8.Nb3  with idea of Re1, Bf1, Bg5 and a timely Nd5 jump Depending on what White does Black either strikes in the center or expands on the queenside with a6 & b5. }
8. Nb3
{ White removes the knight from d4 to take full control of the d5-outpost and prepares for the strategic fight. }
8... Nc6 9. Bg5 a6 { with a standard idea to expand with ...b5 next } 10. f4 b5
{ Both sides are executing their plans: White wants to establish the bishop on f3 while Black is planning to push ...b4 }
11. Bf3 b4 { Driving the knight towards d5 or away from the center } 12. Na4
{ White's best try. } 12... Bd7
{ More accurate than 12...Bb7 with idea to put pressure on the a4-knight. } 13.
a3 Qc7 14. Kh1
{ 14.axb4  Nxb4  15.c3  Nc6  with eventual pressure on the b-file. Both of White's knights are stranded. }
14... a5
{ A natural novelty to continue the logical plan of expansion on the queenside. }
15. axb4 axb4 16. e5 { White desperately needs counterplay } 16... dxe5 17.
fxe5 Nxe5 { An instructive exchange sac à la Petrosian! } 18. Bxa8 Rxa8 19.
Nac5 Bc6 20. Rxa8+ Bxa8
{ Black's piercing bishops and the extra pawn give us full compensation for the exchange! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4) The Daring Dragondorf [Alternative]"]
[Black "5.Nc3 d6 6.Be3 Bg7 7.f3 a6 8.g4 h5 "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 g6
{ This is the Hyper-Accelerated Dragon move order. Black's idea is to fianchetto the bishop on g7 first, controlling the long diagonal.   Please note that we avoid  2...Nc6  as it allows  3.Bb5  which is known as the Rossolimo Variation, which leads to totally different types of positions. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6
{ This is my recommended way to play this opening as by attacking the e4-pawn we sidestep the Maroczy Bind  4...Nc6  4.c4  . }
5. Nc3 d6 6. Be3 Bg7 7. f3 a6
{ Black doesn't commit the king and instead plays a useful move 7...a6 à la Najdorf. }
8. g4
{ A tricky move, anticipating ...h5, but as long as Black doesn't castle right away they are fine }
8... h5 { We still follow-through with our setup! } 9. g5 Nfd7 10. Qd2 O-O
{ Since the kingside is closed we are safe to castle! } 11. O-O-O b5
{ Remember: the Dragon@@StartBracket@@dorf@@EndBracket@@ swings with the tail! }
12. f4 b4 13. Nd5 e6
{ Black happily sacs the b4-pawn to open up files against the enemy king. } 14.
Nxb4 Bb7 15. Bg2 Nb6
{ Black has full compensation and a strong attack with ideas like ...Nc4 & ...a5 next. }
