15. Nxe4 Bxd4+ 16. Kh1 Qxd2 17. Nxd2 Bxb2
{ Black's bishop gives us a clear edge. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4) The Daring Dragondorf [Alternative]"]
[Black "9.a4 Nc6 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 g6
{ This is the Hyper-Accelerated Dragon move order. Black's idea is to fianchetto the bishop on g7 first, controlling the long diagonal.   Please note that we avoid  2...Nc6  as it allows  3.Bb5  which is known as the Rossolimo Variation, which leads to totally different types of positions. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6
{ This is my recommended way to play this opening as by attacking the e4-pawn we sidestep the Maroczy Bind  4...Nc6  4.c4  . }
5. Nc3 d6 6. Be3 Bg7 7. f3 a6
{ Black doesn't commit the king and instead plays a useful move 7...a6 à la Najdorf. }
8. Qd2 h5
{ We've reached the main Dragondorf tabiya. White has several plans:  1@@EndBracket@@  9.O-O-O  right away or  9.Bc4  first, then castle long.  2@@EndBracket@@  9.a4  to stop the expansion with ...b5.  3@@EndBracket@@  9.Nd5  to play for the bind with c4.  4@@EndBracket@@ Tricky waiting moves  9.Be2  or  9.h3  . }
9. a4 Nc6
{ Now that White has committed to a4, he's unlikely to castle queenside. In this case play like the regular Dragon. }
10. Bc4 Qa5 11. O-O Qb4
{ I like this idea, similar to the Accelerated Dragon, Black sets up a nice tactic }
12. Bb3 Nxd4 13. Bxd4
{ This natural move is the wrong recapture! Now, Black uncorks the key idea coming up next.   13.Qxd4!  Qxd4  14.Bxd4  O-O=  with a typical balanced Dragon endgame. }
13... Nxe4 14. Bxf7+ { White's only chance to stay in the game. } 14... Kd8
{ A simple sidestep away from the f-file and Black is better in all lines, for example: }
15. fxe4 Qxd4+ 16. Qxd4 Bxd4+ 17. Kh1 g5
{ Black is better due to the bishop pair. } *

