[White "4) The Daring Dragondorf [Alternative]"]
[Black "9.Be2 Nc6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 g6
{ This is the Hyper-Accelerated Dragon move order. Black's idea is to fianchetto the bishop on g7 first, controlling the long diagonal.   Please note that we avoid  2...Nc6  as it allows  3.Bb5  which is known as the Rossolimo Variation, which leads to totally different types of positions. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6
{ This is my recommended way to play this opening as by attacking the e4-pawn we sidestep the Maroczy Bind  4...Nc6  4.c4  . }
5. Nc3 d6 6. Be3 Bg7 7. f3 a6
{ Black doesn't commit the king and instead plays a useful move 7...a6 à la Najdorf. }
8. Qd2 h5
{ We've reached the main Dragondorf tabiya. White has several plans:  1@@EndBracket@@  9.O-O-O  right away or  9.Bc4  first, then castle long.  2@@EndBracket@@  9.a4  to stop the expansion with ...b5.  3@@EndBracket@@  9.Nd5  to play for the bind with c4.  4@@EndBracket@@ Tricky waiting moves  9.Be2  or  9.h3  . }
9. Be2
{ This is a sneaky waiting move. White is not committing to either of the plans and can still play 10.a4 or 10.O-O-O. }
9... Nc6
{ I like this move, indicating that we're not afraid of the Dragon!   9...Nbd7  allows White to get a Maroczy bind setup after  10.a4  b6  11.Nd5  Bb7  12.c4∞  the position is quite complex and totally playable for Black. But since I'm trying to avoid the bind in this course, I won't recommend it. }
10. O-O-O
{ A principled approach.   10.O-O  Nxd4  11.Bxd4  O-O=  leads to a typical Dragon where White castles kingside with roughly an even game. }
10... Bd7
{ Basically we have a regular Dragon with h5 & a6 and White played Be2. Engines, of course, prefer White, but the deeper you go, the more they change their mind. Black has some cool attacking ideas here! }
11. Kb1 { A typical move in the Dragon. } 11... Rc8 12. h3
{ The most common move, and we actually transposed to a blitz game: Jacobson, B - Nakamura, H, 2020. }
12... h4
{ This is the key move that slows down White's counterplay on the kingside! }
13. f4 b5 { Hikaru's choice and the most logical way to attack. } 14. a3
{ 14.Bf3!?  perhaps a better try   @@StartBracket@@  14...Qc7!?  is also worth considering, building up the attack.@@EndBracket@@  14...Na5  15.b3  Qc7  , now the game simplifies to an endgame  16.Nd5  Nxd5  17.exd5  Qc3  18.Qxc3  Rxc3  White may be a bit better, but Black has plenty of resources. }
14... O-O
{ Even better than Nakamura's  14...Qc7  . Black invites White to win the pawn with 15.Bf2 . }
15. Bf2 { Too slow and allows us a nice attack.   15.Bf3  Na5! } 15... b4
{ Black rips open the queenside. } 16. axb4 Nxb4 17. Bxh4
{ This allows a crushing sacrifice. } 17... Nxe4
{ An instructive sac in these Dragon positions. } 18. Nxe4 Qa5 19. Nc3 Bf5
{ Black brings the bishop into the attack, and White is hopelessly pinned down. }
20. Nb3 { 20.Nxf5  Bxc3-+ } 20... Rxc3 21. Nxa5 Bxc2+ 22. Qxc2
{ 22.Kc1  Na2#   22.Ka1  22...Ra3# } 22... Rxc2
{ With the unstoppable threats of ...Rxe2 or ...Rxb2. } *

