{ This is the Hyper-Accelerated Dragon move order. Black's idea is to fianchetto the bishop on g7 first, controlling the long diagonal.   Please note that we avoid  2...Nc6  as it allows  3.Bb5  which is known as the Rossolimo Variation, which leads to totally different types of positions. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6
{ This is my recommended way to play this opening as by attacking the e4-pawn we sidestep the Maroczy Bind  4...Nc6  4.c4  . }
5. Nc3 d6 6. Be3 Bg7 7. f3 a6
{ Black doesn't commit the king and instead plays a useful move 7...a6 à la Najdorf. }
8. Qd2 h5
{ We've reached the main Dragondorf tabiya. White has several plans:  1@@EndBracket@@  9.O-O-O  right away or  9.Bc4  first, then castle long.  2@@EndBracket@@  9.a4  to stop the expansion with ...b5.  3@@EndBracket@@  9.Nd5  to play for the bind with c4.  4@@EndBracket@@ Tricky waiting moves  9.Be2  or  9.h3  . }
9. O-O-O { This is the most popular move by far with 237 games in the DB. }
9... b5 { Black grabs more space and now has the option of ...Bb7 fianchetto. }
10. Kb1
{ This is a typical Sicilian move. White's king is almost always useful on b1, so this tempo loss is not critical. }
10... Bb7
{ Black develops his bishop and takes control over the d5-outpost. White doesn't have a typical pawn storm on the kingside and lacks a clear plan. I have analyzed this position quite deeply and would love to share with you some cool ideas! }
11. a3 { Most common move. White stops ...b4 } 11... Nbd7
{ Black completes development and has a nice flexible structure. White lacks a clear plan. Let's take a look at some typical lines.   12.Nb3  Rc8  13.Be2  Qc7  would transpose. }
12. Be2 Qc7
{ A bit more flexible than  12...Rc8  , but both are totally playable. Please note that Black is not interested in castling yet as the king is quite safe on e8! }
13. h3 { with idea to play g4 is met with instructive } 13... h4
{ Black locks up the kingside and ready to attack for free on the queenside! For example: }
14. Bg5 Nb6 15. Qe1 Rb8 { Black happily sacs the h4-pawn for attack. } 16. Bxh4
O-O
{ Now that White has no attack, it's time to activate the h8-rook. Black's attack is much faster, for example: }
17. g4 Rfc8 18. Bf2 Na4 19. Nxa4 bxa4 20. h4 { Allows an instructive finish. }
20... Nxe4 { 20...Bxe4!  this wins as well! } 21. fxe4 Bxe4 22. Bd3 Bxh1 23.
Qxh1 Qc3 { Crushing! } *

