1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 g6
{ This is the Hyper-Accelerated Dragon move order. Black's idea is to fianchetto the bishop on g7 first, controlling the long diagonal.   Please note that we avoid  2...Nc6  as it allows  3.Bb5  which is known as the Rossolimo Variation, which leads to totally different types of positions. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6
{ This is my recommended way to play this opening as by attacking the e4-pawn we sidestep the Maroczy Bind  4...Nc6  4.c4  . }
5. f3
{ It's a rare move with about 70 games in DB. White wants to play c4 and transpose into the Maroczy Bind. However, with accurate moves, we will avoid the main line and fight for the advantage! }
5... Nc6 6. c4 Bg7
{ Creating a hidden threat if White plays a natural  7.Nc3  . } 7. Nc2
{ White removes the knight from the center hoping to build the longterm bind and avoid any trades. However, slow play in the opening is usually punished with active play. After: }
7... O-O 8. Nc3 e6 { Preparing the ...d5 pawn sac. } 9. Be2 d5
{ Black blows open the center and gets a nice initiative. } 10. cxd5 exd5 11.
Nxd5 Nxd5 12. exd5 Ne7 13. Ne3 Nf5 14. Nxf5 { 14.O-O?  Bd4  wins a piece. }
14... Bxf5 15. O-O Rc8
{ Black's active pieces give us more than sufficient compensation for the pawn. White is having a hard time developing the queenside. }
