{ Remember this move!   7...Nb6  8.a4!  with a threat of a5, Black's knight is running out of room. }
8. Bc4 Ne6
{ Black completes the knight regrouping and threatens ...Na5 to win the bishop pair. }
9. Bxe6
{ 9.O-O  Na5!  10.Qc3  Nxc4  11.Qxc4  b6  ⩱ followed with ...Bb7 and easy game. }
9... dxe6
{ 9...fxe6!?  this is also ok with the idea of using the f-file in the future.  10.O-O  Bg7  11.Bf4  O-O  12.Bg3  b5!  with a complex game. }
10. O-O Bg7 11. Bf4 O-O 12. Nc3 Nd4
{ Even better than  12...Qa5  , which I played vs. David Pruess back in 2006. }
13. Nxd4 Qxd4 14. g3 Bxe5 { why not grab a central pawn? } 15. Rad1
{ 15.Nb5  Qc5!  16.Be3!  Qc6  17.Nxa7!  is a crazy computer line, but Black is a bit better after  17...Qa6⩱  . }
15... Qc5 16. Na4 Qc7
{ And White doesn't have full compensation for the pawn as in the game: Zirdum,I @@StartBracket@@2069@@EndBracket@@-Huddleston,H @@StartBracket@@1746@@EndBracket@@ West Ryde 2004. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6) 2.Nf3 g6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Qxd4"]
[Black "4.Qxd4 Nf6 5.e5 Nc6 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 g6
{ This is the Hyper-Accelerated Dragon move order. Black's idea is to fianchetto the bishop on g7 first, controlling the long diagonal.   Please note that we avoid  2...Nc6  as it allows  3.Bb5  which is known as the Rossolimo Variation, which leads to totally different types of positions. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Qxd4
{ This is a popular way to try to punish us for the HAD move order. However, I believe that these positions are easier to play as Black since the queen on d4 is an easy target. I have won many games in this line and always happy to see it on the board! }
4... Nf6
{ Black develops the knight and stops the obvious threat. Now, we plan to win a tempo with ...Nc6! }
5. e5 { This used to be the main line, but now it's a bit less popular. } 5...
Nc6 6. Qa4
{ 6.Qh4?  leads to a similar fate for the e5-pawn  6...Nxe5!  7.Nxe5  Qa5+∓  . }
6... Nd5 7. Qe4 Nb6 { I think this is a more flexible square than c7 } 8. Bf4
d5 { Black plays a series of tempo moves to gain the initiative. } 9. exd6 Bf5
{ 10.dxe7?  Bxe7  11.Qe2  O-O∓  with big threats like ...Re8 and ...Nb4 Black is close to winning as White seriously lacks development. }
10. Qe2 Nd5 { Black activates the knight with a tempo! } 11. Be5 f6 12. Bg3 e5
{ This is even stronger than my previous attempts  12...Qa5+  vs Shabalov in 2009 and  12...Ndb4!?  vs Kiewra in 2010. }
13. Nxe5
{ White is more or less forced to play this as they can't develop the pieces. }
13... fxe5 14. Bxe5 Kf7 { A brilliant idea, Black sacs the rook on h8. } 15.
Bxh8 Qxd6
{ Despite being down material, Black is close to winning.   @@StartBracket@@  15...Bxd6∓  is also strong@@EndBracket@@  The big threats are ...Re8 and ...Ndb4. Two games reached this position in the DB. Let's examine White's options here: }
16. Qd1 Re8+ { The simplest, but other moves win as well } 17. Be2 Bg4 18. f3
Qc5 { This is a hard move to find, but Black is totally winning now. } 19. fxg4
Kg8
{ Another hard move, Black wants to play ...Nf4 or ...Ne3.   19...Nf4?  20.Rf1!  and Black is losing now. }
20. Bc3 Nf4 { And White's king is just too exposed. } *

