1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 g6
{ This is the Hyper-Accelerated Dragon move order. Black's idea is to fianchetto the bishop on g7 first, controlling the long diagonal.   Please note that we avoid  2...Nc6  as it allows  3.Bb5  which is known as the Rossolimo Variation, which leads to totally different types of positions. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Qxd4
{ This is a popular way to try to punish us for the HAD move order. However, I believe that these positions are easier to play as Black since the queen on d4 is an easy target. I have won many games in this line and always happy to see it on the board! }
4... Nf6
{ Black develops the knight and stops the obvious threat. Now, we plan to win a tempo with ...Nc6! }
5. e5 { This used to be the main line, but now it's a bit less popular. } 5...
Nc6 6. Qa4
{ 6.Qh4?  leads to a similar fate for the e5-pawn  6...Nxe5!  7.Nxe5  Qa5+∓  . }
6... Nd5 7. Qe4 Nb6 { I think this is a more flexible square than c7 } 8. Nc3
d5 { Black strikes in the center and attacks White's misplaced queen. } 9. exd6
Bf5 { Rapid development is key here! } 10. Qe2 Qxd6 11. Nb5 Qb8
{ Black keeps the queen on the h2-b8 diagonal to stop Bf4. } 12. Nbd4 Bg7
{ Black continues with natural development and is not worried about the trade on f5.   12...Nxd4!?  is also an interesting try  13.Nxd4  Bd7  14.Bg5  e5!  15.Bf6  Bb4+!  16.c3  O-O!  with complications that are fine for Black. }
13. Nxf5 gxf5 14. g3
{ White tries to get the bishop to h3/g2 so that they can castle. } 14... Qd6
15. Bg2 { Allows a cool trick! } 15... Qb4+ 16. c3 Bxc3+ 17. bxc3 Qxc3+ 18. Qd2
Qxa1 { Winning material and the game, game over. } *

