{ Black develops the knight and stops the obvious threat. Now, we plan to win a tempo with ...Nc6! }
5. e5 { This used to be the main line, but now it's a bit less popular. } 5...
Nc6 6. Qa4
{ 6.Qh4?  leads to a similar fate for the e5-pawn  6...Nxe5!  7.Nxe5  Qa5+∓  . }
6... Nd5 7. Qe4 Nb6 { I think this is a more flexible square than c7 } 8. Nc3
d5 { Black strikes in the center and attacks White's misplaced queen. } 9. exd6
Bf5 { Rapid development is key here! } 10. Qe2 Qxd6 11. Nb5 Qb8
{ Black keeps the queen on the h2-b8 diagonal to stop Bf4. } 12. Nbd4 Bg7
{ Black continues with natural development and is not worried about the trade on f5.   12...Nxd4!?  is also an interesting try  13.Nxd4  Bd7  14.Bg5  e5!  15.Bf6  Bb4+!  16.c3  O-O!  with complications that are fine for Black. }
