[White "6) 2.Nf3 g6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Qxd4"]
[Black "4.Qxd4 Nf6 5.Bb5 a6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 g6
{ This is the Hyper-Accelerated Dragon move order. Black's idea is to fianchetto the bishop on g7 first, controlling the long diagonal.   Please note that we avoid  2...Nc6  as it allows  3.Bb5  which is known as the Rossolimo Variation, which leads to totally different types of positions. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Qxd4
{ This is a popular way to try to punish us for the HAD move order. However, I believe that these positions are easier to play as Black since the queen on d4 is an easy target. I have won many games in this line and always happy to see it on the board! }
4... Nf6
{ Black develops the knight and stops the obvious threat. Now, we plan to win a tempo with ...Nc6! }
5. Bb5
{ White stops ...Nc6 but Black has a simple way to expand on the queenside. }
5... a6 6. e5
{ White enters crazy complications that work out well for Black.   6.Ba4  invites energetic play  6...b5!  7.Bb3  Nc6⩱  and White will lose more tempi. }
6... axb5 7. exf6 Nc6
{ Black is not wasting any time on slow  7...exf6?  and develops instead! } 8.
Qe3 { White pins the e-pawn making it harder to develop our kingside. } 8... b4
{ An amazing move. This little pawn paralyzed White's queenside and makes it hard to develop the b1-knight. }
9. O-O e6
{ Black will take on f6 next. Let me show you a cool idea if White tries to hang on to the pawn: }
10. Qf4 { is met with } 10... h6 { followed by ...g5 next } 11. h4 g5 12. hxg5
hxg5 13. Nxg5 d5 { with idea ...Bd6 and a crushing attack. } *

