[Round "?"]
[White "6) 2.Nf3 g6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Qxd4"]
[Black "4.Qxd4 Nf6 5.Bb5 a6 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 g6
{ This is the Hyper-Accelerated Dragon move order. Black's idea is to fianchetto the bishop on g7 first, controlling the long diagonal.   Please note that we avoid  2...Nc6  as it allows  3.Bb5  which is known as the Rossolimo Variation, which leads to totally different types of positions. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Qxd4
{ This is a popular way to try to punish us for the HAD move order. However, I believe that these positions are easier to play as Black since the queen on d4 is an easy target. I have won many games in this line and always happy to see it on the board! }
4... Nf6
{ Black develops the knight and stops the obvious threat. Now, we plan to win a tempo with ...Nc6! }
5. Bb5
{ White stops ...Nc6 but Black has a simple way to expand on the queenside. }
5... a6 6. e5
{ White enters crazy complications that work out well for Black.   6.Ba4  invites energetic play  6...b5!  7.Bb3  Nc6⩱  and White will lose more tempi. }
6... axb5 7. exf6 Nc6
{ Black is not wasting any time on slow  7...exf6?  and develops instead! } 8.
fxe7
{ This is the most common move and was played by MVL back in 2017 when he was rated 2803! }
8... Qxe7+ 9. Qe3
{ White would like to trade queens and get a favorable pawn structure in the endgame. }
9... b4
{ This is the key idea that was shown to me by Dzindzi back in 1997! Black stops the b1 knight from developing to a natural c3 square. }
10. O-O
{ 10.Kd1?  I faced this move in World Open 1998 and won a memorable game  10...Qxe3  11.Bxe3  Bg7∓  see the model game: Bryan, J @@StartBracket@@2265@@EndBracket@@-Perelshteyn, E @@StartBracket@@2375@@EndBracket@@ Philadelphia 1998. }
10... Qxe3 11. Bxe3 Bg7 12. c3 O-O
{ Black's monster bishop on g7 together with b4-pawn make it tough for White to get the b1-knight developed. }
13. Rd1 d5 { An instructive pawn sacrifice to develop the c8-bishop } 14. Nd4
{ White's most common move.   14.Rxd5  is probably the best try, but after  14...Be6  15.Rc5  Rfd8  16.Nbd2  bxc3  17.bxc3  Nb4⩱  Black is having all the fun! }
14... Bg4 { Black induces f3 to gain a tempo next move } 15. f3 Rfe8 16. Kf2
Bd7
{ Black has finished development and stands better. White is still stuck as natural }
17. Nd2 { Runs into the spectacular } 17... Rxe3 18. Kxe3 Re8+ 19. Kd3 Nxd4 20.
cxd4 Bf5+ { Winning on the spot. } *

