17. Nd2 { Runs into the spectacular } 17... Rxe3 18. Kxe3 Re8+ 19. Kf2 Nxd4 20.
cxd4 Bxd4+ 21. Kg3 Bxb2 22. Rab1 Bc3
{ with two pawns and a bishop pair Black has more than enough for the exchange. The engine even says Black is totally winning! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6) 2.Nf3 g6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Qxd4"]
[Black "4.Qxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 Nc6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 g6
{ This is the Hyper-Accelerated Dragon move order. Black's idea is to fianchetto the bishop on g7 first, controlling the long diagonal.   Please note that we avoid  2...Nc6  as it allows  3.Bb5  which is known as the Rossolimo Variation, which leads to totally different types of positions. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Qxd4
{ This is a popular way to try to punish us for the HAD move order. However, I believe that these positions are easier to play as Black since the queen on d4 is an easy target. I have won many games in this line and always happy to see it on the board! }
4... Nf6
{ Black develops the knight and stops the obvious threat. Now, we plan to win a tempo with ...Nc6! }
5. Nc3
{ This move is currently the most popular way to play for White. It's the choice for most top GMs, and I see it all the time in blitz. }
5... Nc6 6. Qa4 d6 7. e5
{ This is the point of White's previous moves. Now, Black has to deal with the pin and pressure in the center. }
7... dxe5 8. Nxe5 Bd7
{ I recommend this natural move as it's easier to learn and a safer option for Black.   8...Bg7!?  is also a good try, as recommended in Giri's Chessable course on the Dragon. However,  8...Bd7  is more solid and easier to play. }
9. Nxd7 Nxd7 10. Be3 Bg7 11. O-O-O
{ This is an aggressive try, but White's king also gets exposed. } 11... Bxc3
12. bxc3 Qc7
{ A natural novelty to break the pin. Black now has the option to castle long, for example: }
13. h4 O-O-O 14. h5 Nb6 { With a nice initiative and the safer king! } *

