[Round "?"]
[White "7) Advance Variation 3.c3 d5 4.e5"]
[Black "3.c3 d5 4.e5 Bg4 #11"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 g6
{ This is the Hyper-Accelerated Dragon move order. Black's idea is to fianchetto the bishop on g7 first, controlling the long diagonal.   Please note that we avoid  2...Nc6  as it allows  3.Bb5  which is known as the Rossolimo Variation, which leads to totally different types of positions. }
3. c3 d5
{ We undermine White's center and give him a choice: taking the pawn, transposing to Alapin or play the Advance variation 4.e5. }
4. e5
{ White's most ambitious move.   4.exd5  Qxd5  5.d4  Bg7  see the Alapin chapter. }
4... Bg4
{ I prefer to start with this rare move to pin the knight right away. Most players prefer  4...Nc6  , which gives White some extra options. }
5. d4 cxd4 6. cxd4 Nc6
{ White has several options here, all leading to easy play for Black. } 7. Bb5
{ Preferred choice of Caruana & Nakamura } 7... Rc8
{ I like this simple idea. Now, Black doesn't have to worry about ruining his pawn structure after Bxc6+ as he can take back with the rook. }
8. O-O Qb6
{ This is a rare move that has never been played at the GM level. Black is attacking the bishop while keeping an eye on the d4-pawn, which is White's main weakness. }
9. Bxc6+ Rxc6 10. Nbd2 Bf5
{ Black takes advantage of weakened c2 square, making it harder for White to play Nb3. For example: }
11. Nb3 Bc2 { The point! } 12. Qe2 Bxb3 13. axb3 e6 14. Bg5 h6
{ Giving White a choice, and a chance to go wrong. } 15. Bf6 Nxf6 16. exf6 Bd6
{ With rough equality. } *

