1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 g6
{ This is the Hyper-Accelerated Dragon move order. Black's idea is to fianchetto the bishop on g7 first, controlling the long diagonal.   Please note that we avoid  2...Nc6  as it allows  3.Bb5  which is known as the Rossolimo Variation, which leads to totally different types of positions. }
3. c4
{ This is a rare move to trick us into playing the Maroczy Bind. However, I will show you a cool Anti-Maroczy setup here. }
3... Bg7 4. d4 Qa5+ { This is the key move that sidesteps the typical bind. }
5. Nc3 { White's most popular reply. } 5... d6
{ With this move Black keeps White guessing how he would resolve the center. Our main idea is to apply more pressure with a future ...Nc6 or ...Bg4. }
6. d5
{ This is the most ambitious try. White takes the game into the closed structure that resembles the Dzindzi-Indian. But keep in mind, typically 1.e4 players hate playing closed positions! }
6... Bxc3+
{ The main idea of the Dzindzi-Indian. Black ruins White's structure. } 7. bxc3
Bg4
{ I like this rare move, putting more pressure on White. Keep in mind that in closed positions, knights are better than bishops. }
8. Qc2 { The most common reply, but walks straight into our plan! } 8... Bxf3
9. gxf3
{ This is an interesting position. White's bishop pair and more space are counterbalanced by the weak pawns. I believe the closed nature of the position gives Black better practical chances, even though the engine slightly prefers White at first. }
9... Nd7 10. f4 Ngf6 11. Bd3 { this natural developing move is already wrong. }
11... O-O-O
{ The key idea to remember! We typically castle long so that we can attack White on the kingside! }
12. O-O h6
{ A nice idea that was played by a strong Russian GM Malakhov back in 2016. Black is ready to blow open the kingside with ...g5! }
13. Re1
{ White is seeking counterplay with e5.   13.Be3?!  allows our main idea!  13...g5!  14.fxg5?  hxg5∓  with a killer attack. }
13... Qc7 14. Qe2 e5
{ preventing White from playing e5 himself! Now, we get an endgame almost by force: }
15. dxe6 fxe6 16. e5
{ White has to open up the game in order not to be worse.   16.Be3  e5∓  . }
16... dxe5 17. fxe5 Qxe5 18. Qxe5 Nxe5 19. Rxe5 Rxd3 20. Rxc5+ Kd8
{ The endgame is about equal and Black eventually won the game: Kreisl, R  @@StartBracket@@2448@@EndBracket@@-Malakhov, V @@StartBracket@@2698@@EndBracket@@ Novi Sad 2016. }
