[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9) 3.Bc4 Setup"]
[Black "3.Bc4 Bg7 4.O-O d6 #7"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 g6
{ This is the Hyper-Accelerated Dragon move order. Black's idea is to fianchetto the bishop on g7 first, controlling the long diagonal.   Please note that we avoid  2...Nc6  as it allows  3.Bb5  which is known as the Rossolimo Variation, which leads to totally different types of positions. }
3. Bc4
{ White goes for natural development first, keeping the option to play d3 or c3 & d4 next. }
3... Bg7 4. O-O d6
{ Black is going for the typical Dragon now, knowing that it's not dangerous when White castles kingside. }
5. c3 { White aims to win the center with d4 next. } 5... Nf6
{ Rapid development and attacking the e4-pawn. } 6. Re1 O-O 7. Bb3
{ White sidesteps our threat of ...Nxe4 & d5. } 7... Nc6 8. h3 e5
{ Black anticipates d4 and is ready to liquidate in the center. } 9. d4
{ 9.d3  b5!  10.a4  b4!  with counterplay. } 9... exd4 10. cxd4 cxd4 11. Nxd4
Nxd4 12. Qxd4 Be6
{ Black's better development compensates for his d6 weakness. White has to deal with threats of 13...d5 or 13...Nd5. The position is about even. }
*

