1. e4 c5 2. c3 d5
{ For this course I'm sticking with one of the best ways to neutralize the Alapin. We will take on d5 with the queen and play ...g6 in the spirit of the Dragon!   The great thing about this line is that you kill two birds with one stone as White often plays @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  g6  3.c3  and now we just transpose to the Alapin with  3...d5  4.exd5  Qxd5  .   2...g6  is what I recommended in Chess Openings Explained back in 2005 but White can fight for a small edge after  3.d4  cxd4  4.cxd4  d5  5.e5! }
3. exd5 Qxd5 4. d4 g6
{ We still fianchetto the bishop, and while it's the 5th most played move, it has the best scoring statistic in the DB for Black!  Here's a comparison @@StartBracket@@win % from White point of@@EndBracket@@:  ➥  4...Nf6  50.9%  ➥  4...Nc6  53.5%  ➥  4...e6  52.9%  ➥  4...cxd4  57.7%  ➥  4...g6  43.8% }
5. dxc5 Qxc5 6. Be3 Qc7 { The queen is well-placed on c7 } 7. Na3 a6
{ Stopping Nb5. } 8. Nc4 Nd7 9. a4 Bg7 10. a5
{ White secures the b6-outpost, but Black has an instructive way to drive the bishop away from e3 and free up the position. }
10... Nh6 { An instructive idea, the knight is heading to f5. } 11. Nf3 Nf5 12.
Bb6 Nxb6 13. Nxb6 Rb8
{ Black is rock solid and will finish development next with ...O-O. } 14. Bc4
O-O 15. O-O Nd6 16. Bb3 Bd7
{ The bishop is heading to c6 with a comfortable game for Black. } *

