[White "11) Alapin 2.c3"]
[Black "6.Na3 cxd4 7.Nb5 Na6 #9"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. c3 d5
{ For this course I'm sticking with one of the best ways to neutralize the Alapin. We will take on d5 with the queen and play ...g6 in the spirit of the Dragon!   The great thing about this line is that you kill two birds with one stone as White often plays @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  g6  3.c3  and now we just transpose to the Alapin with  3...d5  4.exd5  Qxd5  .   2...g6  is what I recommended in Chess Openings Explained back in 2005 but White can fight for a small edge after  3.d4  cxd4  4.cxd4  d5  5.e5! }
3. exd5 Qxd5 4. d4 g6
{ We still fianchetto the bishop, and while it's the 5th most played move, it has the best scoring statistic in the DB for Black!  Here's a comparison @@StartBracket@@win % from White point of@@EndBracket@@:  ➥  4...Nf6  50.9%  ➥  4...Nc6  53.5%  ➥  4...e6  52.9%  ➥  4...cxd4  57.7%  ➥  4...g6  43.8% }
5. Nf3 { We can reach this exact position with the 2.Nf3 & 3.c3 move order. }
5... Bg7
{ This setup scores really well for Black vs. the Alapin in the DB. It's recommended by Giri in his Dragon Lifetime Chessable course.   Young Uzbek superstar Abdusattorov is also a big fan as you can see from the recent games. }
6. Na3
{ This is the most popular and also recommended by SuperGM Wesley So in his Chessable course. }
6... cxd4 7. Nb5 { Wesley's recommendation, also played by Magnus vs Giri. }
7... Na6 { We have to stop the Nc7+ family fork. } 8. Nbxd4 Nf6
{ In this line Black typically doesn't mind ruining his pawn structure after  9.Bxa6  as the bishop pair will give him long-term dynamic play. }
9. Bb5+
{ White typically forces the bishop on d7 prior to taking on a6, so that Black's bishop can't go to b7 in one move. }
9... Bd7 10. Bxa6
{ White's most ambitious move. He gives up the bishop pair but damages Black's pawns. }
10... bxa6 11. O-O O-O 12. Re1
{ White stops e5 push and puts extra pressure on the half-open e-file. However, I will share with you a simple regrouping plan to achieve a comfortable game. }
12... Rfe8 13. Ne5 Bc8
{ This is the key move to transfer the bishop to b7. I don't believe this move is covered by Wesley So in his Chessable course. }
14. c4 { This natural move was seen in two games in the DB. } 14... Qd6 15. Qf3
Rb8 { And here I analyzed two logical moves for White: } 16. Nb3 Bb7 17. Qe2
Ne4 18. Nf3 Qb4
{ 0-1 Bokhnak,T @@StartBracket@@1855@@EndBracket@@-Svobodova,M @@StartBracket@@1934@@EndBracket@@ Brno 2021. }
