[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "12) Closed Sicilian 2.Nc3 g6 3.g3"]
[Black "2.Nc3 g6 3.g3 Bg7 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 g6 3. g3 Bg7 4. Bg2 Nc6 5. d3 d6
{ We've reached a classic Closed Sicilian pawn structure.   Notice how the pawn chains will determine the plans for both sides: White's pawn chain of c2-d3-e4 dictates that they should play for the kingside attack with a future f4-f5 plan. Black, on the other hand, will prepare the tail swing with a future b5-b4. }
6. f4 e6
{ I like this way of developing against the early f4. Black will play 7...Nge7 and make it quite hard for White to execute their main plan of f5. }
7. Nf3 Nge7 8. O-O { 8.Be3  Nd4  9.O-O  would transpose after  9...O-O  . }
8... O-O 9. Be3 Nd4
{ This is the key idea to remember. Whenever White is ready to play d4, we prevent it by putting the knight there! }
10. Qd2 Rb8 11. Nd1 b5 12. c3 Nxf3+ 13. Bxf3 b4
{ Black is first to achieve their plan, while it's unclear how White can attack the kingside. }
*

