1. e4 c5 2. Nc3
{ I recommend this move in my White's course: Grand Prix Attack Reloaded. But, I will share with you a fresh way to avoid any attack! }
2... g6
{ We still choose our favorite move order, since  2...Nc6  invites  3.Bb5  . }
3. f4 Bg7 4. Nf3 a6
{ This rare move was only played in 137 games in my DB, compared to  4...Nc6  , which has over 3200 games!   Black immediately stops White's main idea of 5.Bb5 and also discourages  5.Bc4  due to  5...b5! }
5. g3
{ White takes the game to Closed Sicilian, thinking that the extra tempo on a6 will help him. In reality, ...a6 is quite a useful move since Black wants to play ...b5 in the future. I believe Closed Sicilian is not dangerous when Black is able to fianchetto his bishop as it's quite hard for White to create an attack. }
5... Nc6 6. Bg2 d6 7. O-O Nf6
{ I prefer the simple setup with Nf6, but ...e6 & Nge7 is playable as well. }
8. d3 O-O 9. h3 b5
{ Black starts his counterplay right away. At first, it looks a bit risky as it allows 10.e5, but I found an amazing idea that I wanted to share with you: }
10. e5 Ne8 11. exd6 Ra7 { An amazing pawn sac to gain the initiative. } 12.
dxe7 Rxe7
{ Black's active pieces and control of d4-outpost give him full compensation for the pawn. For example:  13.Ne4  c4!  14.Kh2  Nf6  15.Nxf6+  Bxf6  16.dxc4  Rd7!  17.Qe2  Re8!  with a big initiative! }
