1. e4 c5 2. g3
{ This is a somewhat tricky system, White is playing the Closed Sicilian with the knight on b1. The point is that they may try c3 & d4 later to take over the center. }
2... g6 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. Ne2
{ 4.Nc3  Nc6  transposes to Closed Sicilian covered here. } 4... Nc6 5. O-O d6
6. c3
{ White aims to play d4 and take over the center. Therefore we must stop it at once! }
6... e5
{ This is the key move that stops White's main idea. The only drawback is the weakness of d5. However, as you will see it would take White too long to reroute the knight there, while Black will generate rapid counterplay. }
7. d3 h5
{ I'd like to recommend this aggressive idea, which was only seen in 3 games. The point is to play for ...h4 and delay castling.   7...Nge7  this is a standard move here, after  8.Be3  O-O  9.f4  Rb8  with complex play. }
8. h4
{ The inclusion of h5 & h4 favors Black as it's much harder for White to play f4 due to the weakness on g4. }
8... Nge7 9. Be3 O-O 10. Na3 { 10.f4?  weakens the g4-outpost  10...Bg4∓ }
10... Bg4 { Inducing another weakness. } 11. f3 Be6 12. d4 exd4 13. cxd4 d5
{ Remember this key idea! Black takes over the game now. } 14. dxc5 dxe4 15.
fxe4 Bxb2
{ Remember after  16.Nc2  Qa5!  Black is not interested in winning the exchange as the dark-squared bishop is a monster. We want to play ...Rad8 with a big initiative as White's structure is severely damaged. }
