[Black "2.c4 g6 3.Nc3 Bg7 4.g3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. c4
{ White plans to play Nc3, g3, Bg2, Nge2 with a flexible setup known as the Botvinnik English since he can also start with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.c4  . }
2... g6 3. Nc3 { 3.Nf3  Bg7!  4.d4  Qa5+!  see 2.Nf3 & c4 Anti-Maroczy Setup. }
3... Bg7 4. g3 Nc6 5. Bg2 a6
{ A rare move that many White players underestimate and answer with the autopilot  6.Nge2  . }
6. a4
{ This is a solid choice, stopping ...b5. However, now White is saddled with two glaring weaknesses: d4 & b4 holes. }
6... d6
{ I'm sticking with this standard Dragon structure throughout my course. But also strong is 6...e6 and Nge7 setup. }
7. Nge2 Bg4
{ I prefer to ask White a question with this move. Does he play weakening f3/h3 or allow the annoying pin? }
8. h3 Bxe2
{ Black's strategic aim is to win the d4-outpost, thus trading the bishop for the knight is a good idea! }
9. Nxe2 Nf6
{ 9...e6  this is also quite strong:  10.O-O  Nge7  11.d3  Rb8  12.Rb1  b5⩱  . }
10. O-O Nd7 11. d3 Nf8 { An interesting idea to fight for d4-outpost via e6. }
12. f4 Ne6 13. f5 Ned4
{ Black controls all the key dark squares and stands better. White has no clear plan. }
*

