1. e4 c5 2. b4
{ The Wing Gambit is not very sound, but you do need to know some theory! }
2... cxb4 { Of course, we take the pawn! } 3. a3 e5
{ This is the fourth most played move, but I believe it's the simplest way to punish the gambit. }
4. Nf3 Nc6 5. Bc4 Nf6 6. Qe2 Be7
{ Black just wants to finish development and maintain the extra pawn. } 7. axb4
Bxb4 8. c3 Be7 9. O-O O-O 10. d4 d6
{ This position resembles the Evans Gambit. However, White's compensation is barely enough for the pawn. }
11. Rd1 Qc7
{ A natural square for the queen as she steps out of the x-ray of White's rook. Black's plan is to play ...h6, Re8 and Bf8 to solidify the kingside and eventually convert the extra pawn. For example: }
12. h3 h6 13. Nbd2 Re8 14. Nf1 Bf8 15. Ng3 exd4 16. Nxd4 { 16.cxd4  d5! } 16...
d5 17. Nb5 Qb8 { The only move for Black to maintain the advantage! } 18. Bxd5
Nxd5 19. Rxd5 a6 20. Nd4 Nxd4 21. cxd4 b5 22. Qd3 Be6
{ And Black eventually won in this correspondence game: Lipecki, A @@StartBracket@@2341@@EndBracket@@-Bellegotti, G @@StartBracket@@2447@@EndBracket@@ ICCF email 2017. }
