[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "23) Kronberger Variation 2.Na3"]
[Black "2.Na3 g6 3.c3 Bg7 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Na3
{ This unusual move was popularized by the Russian GM Vadim Zvjagintsev. These days both Carlsen and Rapport play it from time to time. The point is to delay c3 and wait for Black to show their plan. }
2... g6 3. c3 Bg7 4. Nf3
{ 4.d4  cxd4  5.cxd4  d5!  Black undermines the center with this thematic idea  6.exd5   @@StartBracket@@  6.e5  a6  with a simple idea to stop Bb5  7.Nf3  Bg4  8.Be2  transposing to the main line 4.Nf3@@EndBracket@@  6...Nf6  and eventually the d5 pawn will be lost. }
4... a6 { I like this unusual move for a specific reason, after: } 5. Be2
{ White could delay d4, but here we can play } 5... d6 6. d4
{ 6.O-O  Nf6!  7.d3  O-O  leads to a passive position for White. Black's plan is quite simple: swing with the tail b5-b4! }
6... cxd4 7. cxd4 Nf6
{ We've reached a non-standard position. White's knight is clearly misplaced on a3, making the job of protecting the e4-pawn quite hard. }
8. Bd3
{ A tempo loss in the opening, but what else to do?   8.e5  dxe5  9.dxe5  Qxd1+  10.Bxd1  Nd5⩱  with a pleasant endgame for Black. }
8... O-O 9. O-O b5
{ The dragon swings with his tail! Black wants to develop with 10...Bb7 and Ndb7. }
10. Re1 Bb7 11. e5 { White's standard central push doesn't work here } 11...
dxe5 12. dxe5 Nfd7 { 13.Bf4  Nc5! } 13. e6 fxe6
{ Black's threats on the f-file are quite serious while it's not clear what White's knight is doing on a3. For example: }
14. Ng5 Nc5 15. Bf1 Qxd1 16. Rxd1 h6 17. Nh3 Nc6
{ Black's extra pawn and better-placed pieces give him a clear edge. } *

