1. e4 c5 2. Bc4 g6 { In this chapter we will cover other moves than  3.Nf3  . }
3. c3 { A tricky move with the idea to meet  3...Bg7  with  4.d4  . } 3... Bg7
4. d4 cxd4 5. cxd4 d5 { A strong idea to remember! } 6. exd5
{ This leads to a comfortable play vs the IQP for Black. } 6... Nd7
{ The knight is heading to b6. } 7. Nc3 Nb6 8. Bb3 Nf6 9. Nf3
{ White typically abandons the d5-pawn. } 9... O-O 10. O-O Nbxd5
{ We've reached a standard position that can arise from many openings such as the Caro-Kann. Black holds comfortable equality here with ...b6 & Bb7. }
