[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Abdelnabbi, I. vs. Firouzja, Alireza (WchT 12th/2019)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 d6 3. f4 g6 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. g3 Nc6 6. Bg2 Nf6 7. d3 O-O 8. O-O
Rb8 9. h3 b5 10. a3 a5 11. g4 b4 12. axb4 axb4 13. Ne2 Bb7 14. Qe1 c4
{ We've covered the theory up to here. } 15. Ng3 cxd3 16. cxd3 Nd7
{ Firouzja shows great understanding of the middlegame and transfers the knight to c5. There's no need to be afraid of White's attack! }
17. Qe2
{ 17.f5  Nc5  18.Qe2  Nb3!  19.Rb1  Nxc1  20.Rbxc1  Qb6+  21.Kh1  Nd4∓  Black takes over the dark squares and stands clearly better }
17... Nc5 { 17...b3∓  with the idea of ...Nb4 could be even stronger! } 18. Be3
Nb3 19. Rab1 Ba6 { Black pins the d-pawn and gets ready to jump to d4. } 20.
Rfd1 Ncd4 21. Nxd4 Bxd4
{ An instructive moment: by trading the dark-square bishops, Firouzja wins the d4-outpost. On the other hand, his king is weakened, but he correctly judges that it's not a big deal. }
22. Bxd4 Nxd4 23. Qf2 e5
{ Securing the knight on e5 and locking White's bishop on g2 forever. } 24. Nf1
{ The only way to fight on.   24.f5?  Rc8  25.Rbc1  Qg5  26.Rxc8  Rxc8∓  and White is strategically lost already! }
24... Qb6 25. Kh2 Rfc8 26. Ne3 Nc2 27. d4
{ White keeps finding only moves to stay afloat. } 27... Nxe3
{ Good call to eliminate White's knight before it gets to d5.   27...Nxd4?  28.Nd5!  with a strong initiative. }
28. Qxe3 Rc4 29. f5
{ White is about to lose the d4-pawn and has to generate counterplay. } 29...
exd4 30. Qh6 Qd8
{ 30...Qc5!?  is a clever way to defend, with the idea of  31.f6?  Qe5+  and the f6-pawn is lost. }
31. Rd2 Qf6 32. Rbd1 Rbc8 33. g5 Qe5+ 34. Kh1 Kh8
{ Preparing to meet f6 with ...Rg8. } 35. f6
{ The losing move!   35.Rf2!  is the only way to keep the game balanced. For example:  35...Rc1  36.Rxc1  Rxc1+  37.Rf1!  Rxf1+  38.Bxf1  Qxe4+  39.Bg2  Qe1+  40.Kh2  Qe5+=  and Black has to give perpetual due to Qf8 mate threat or f6. }
35... Rg8 36. b3 Rcc8 37. Rxd4 Be2
{ A nice tactic, probably missed by White. The rook on d1 is overloaded, protecting the back rank and his buddy on d4. White is lost. }
38. Rd5 Qg3 39. Rg1 Rc2
{ White resigned as the threat of ...Bf3 is unstoppable. } *

