[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Al Awadhi, Waleed vs. Salem, AR. (Asia Cities-ch 18th/2013)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 g6 3. g3 Bg7 4. Bg2 Nc6 5. d3 d6 6. Be3 Nf6 7. h3 O-O 8. Qd2
Nd4 9. Nd1 e5 10. c3 Ne6 11. f4 exf4 12. gxf4 d5
{ We've covered the theory up to here in the Closed Sicilian chapter. } 13. e5
{ A natural move to keep the center closed, but allows Black several strong ideas   13.exd5  Nxd5  Black is clearly better as White's center is shattered and his king is still stuck in the center.   13.f5  gxf5  14.exf5  d4!  is also quite good for Black. }
13... d4
{ 13...Nh5!  is also good  14.Qf2  f6!  Black opens up the f-file and White is close to lost already }
14. exf6 dxe3 15. Nxe3 Bxf6 16. Ng4 { 16.Nf3  drops a pawn  16...Nxf4 } 16...
Bh4+ 17. Nf2
{ Just one look at this position is enough to say that Black is close to winning. White's king is just too weak. }
17... c4 18. d4 Nc5 { A nice tactic to get to the enemy king. } 19. O-O-O
{ 19.dxc5  Re8+  20.Kd1  Bxf2  21.Nf3  Bf5-+  the attack continues even without the queens, White is lost }
19... Bxf2 20. dxc5 { 20.Qxf2  Nd3+  21.Rxd3  cxd3-+ } 20... Qxd2+ 21. Kxd2
{ 21.Rxd2  Be3 } 21... Re8
{ White has survived to reach the endgame, but Black's rooks and bishops are enough to finish off the job. }
22. Ne2 Bf5 23. Bf3 Rad8+ 24. Nd4 { 24.Kc1  Be3+-+  leads to mate } 24... Be3+
{ White resigned as king has to move to the e-file allowing ...Bxd4+ winning a piece }
*

