[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 g6 4. Bc4 Bg7 5. O-O d6 6. d3 e6 7. Be3 Nge7 8. d4
d5 9. Bb5 O-O 10. Bxc6 Nxc6 11. exd5 exd5 12. h3 Bf5
{ We've covered the theory up to this point in the 3.Bc4 setup chapter. } 13.
Bg5 { 13.dxc5?  d4  loses a piece for White. } 13... Qa5
{ Black's bishop pair and strong queenside pressure give him a nice edge. He's not worried about the d5-pawn, as d4 would fall as well. }
14. Nxd5 cxd4 15. Nf6+ Kh8 16. Nxd4 { Allows a beautiful tactical shot. } 16...
Bxc2 17. Nxc6
{ 17.Nxc2  Qxg5  18.Ne4  Qa5  and Black dominates due to the monster bishop on g7. }
17... Qxg5 18. Qxc2 Qxf6 19. Na5
{ White hopes that the game will liquidate to equality after b2 & b7 pawns fall. However, the young Chinese prodigy shows great patience. }
19... Rac8 20. Qa4 Qa6 { Excellent play from Black, White is already lost. }
21. Qb4 b6 22. Nb3 Bxb2
{ Black wins a pawn, but moreover, the bishop still dominates the knight in all endgames. }
23. Nc5 Qa3 24. Qxa3 Bxa3 25. Nd3 Rc2
{ White's totally paralyzed and lost. Black's technique is impeccable. } 26.
Rfd1 Re8 { With the idea to invade on e2. } 27. Ne1 Rce2 28. Kf1 Kg7 29. Nd3
R8e7 30. Re1 Rd2 31. Red1 Ree2 32. Rxd2 Rxd2 33. Nf4 Bd6
{ White resigned as  34.--  34...Be5  is coming, and  a2  falls. A flawless game by Wei Yi! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Bryan, Jarod J vs. Perelshteyn, E. (World op 26th/1998)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 g6
{ This is the Hyper-Accelerated Dragon move order. Black's idea is to fianchetto the bishop on g7 first, controlling the long diagonal.   Please note that we avoid  2...Nc6  as it allows  3.Bb5  which is known as the Rossolimo Variation, which leads to totally different types of positions. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Qxd4 Nf6 5. Bb5 a6 6. e5 axb5 7. exf6 Nc6 8. fxe7 Qxe7+ 9. Qe3 b4
10. Kd1 Qxe3 11. Bxe3 Bg7
{ We've covered the theory up to here in 4.Qxd4 Chapter. } 12. Kc1
{ White has to protect b2 if he wants to develop his queenside   12.c3  doesn't solve the problem for White as he can never take on b4 due to b2 hanging  12...O-O  ∓ }
12... d5 13. Rd1 O-O
{ A natural developing move and an excellent pawn sacrifice. White is way behind in development. }
14. Rxd5 b3 { The 2nd pawn sac opens up the b4 square for my knight } 15. a3
{ 15.cxb3  Nb4  16.Rd2  Nxa2+  17.Kd1  Nc3+!  and picking up a1 rook next }
15... Nb4 { using the simple pin on the a-file } 16. axb4
{ More or less forced, but now White is losing material } 16... Rxa1 17. c3 Bf5
{ the poor knight on b1 never got out } 18. Rxf5 gxf5 19. Nd2
{ Black is up two exchanges and White is still paralyzed. } 19... Ra6 20. Nxb3
Bh6
{ Recognizing that White's kingside pawns are weak, I shift my play there. }
21. f4 { 21.Bxh6  Rxh6  22.h3  Rg6  23.g3  f4-+ } 21... Re8 22. Bd2 Re2
{ This invasion seals the deal, White is totally lost } 23. Nd4 Rxg2 24. Nxf5
Rxh2 25. Na3 Re6 26. Kd1 Re4 27. Nxh6+ Rxh6 28. Nb5 Rh1+ 29. Kc2 h5
{ The h-pawn is unstoppable } 30. Kd3 Re8 31. c4 Rd1 { and White resigned } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Cheng, X. vs. Perelshteyn, E. (World op 34th/2006)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 g6
{ This is the Hyper-Accelerated Dragon move order. Black's idea is to fianchetto the bishop on g7 first, controlling the long diagonal.   Please note that we avoid  2...Nc6  as it allows  3.Bb5  which is known as the Rossolimo Variation, which leads to totally different types of positions. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Qxd4 Nf6 5. e5 Nc6 6. Qa4 Nd5 7. Qe4 Nb6 8. Nc3 d5 9. exd6 Bf5
10. Qe2 Qxd6 11. Nb5 Qb8 12. Nbd4 Bg7 13. Nxf5 gxf5 14. Qb5 e6 15. Bd3 O-O 16.
O-O Rd8 { We've covered the theory up to here in the 4.Qxd4 Chapter. } 17. Bg5
Rd5 { White's queen is misplayed here, and my play is aimed at trapping it! }
18. Qb3 Qd6 { Black's pieces are well-played and I'm threatening ...Na5 } 19.
Rad1
{ Allows my main idea!   19.Bd2!  White has to make this passive move to stop ...Na5, but after  19...Nd7!  with the idea of ...Nc5, Black is still better. }
19... Na5 20. Qa3 Qxa3 21. bxa3
{ The resulting endgame is quite bad for White due to his terrible pawns. }
21... Bb2 { 21...Na4!  may even be a better try } 22. Be7 Nc6 23. Rb1 Nxe7 24.
Rxb2
{ The trade of the dark-square bishops didn't improve White's chances at all. His queenside pawns are waiting to be plucked. }
24... Rc8 25. Nh4 Ng6 26. Nxg6 hxg6 { I love this diamond pawn formation! } 27.
f4 Ra5 28. Rb3 Rc7
{ Black has many winning tries, but I like this simple move to overprotect b7 and enable the knight to move. White has no counterplay. }
29. Re1 Nd7 30. g3 Nc5 31. Rc3 Nxd3
{ Simplifies to a winning rook and pawn endgame. } 32. Rxd3 { 32.Rxc7  Nxe1-+ }
32... Rxc2 33. Rb1 b6 34. Rb4 Rxa2 35. Rc4 R5xa3 36. Rd8+ Kg7
{ And White resigned as the endgame is hopeless. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Ozsoy, Alimert vs. Yilmazyerli, M. (Ayvalik Kumru/2022)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6
{ 2...g6  Please note that this is the move order I recommend in my course to reach the Dragondorf  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  d6  transposing to the game. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6 { We've now transposed into the Dragondorf. }
6. Be3 { White delays f3, but the game will transpose. } 6... a6 7. Qd2 Nbd7
{ Black delays ...h5 until White commits to f3, which is fine. } 8. O-O-O b5 9.
a3 Bb7 10. f3 h5
{ We've now transposed into one of our Dragondorf main lines. } 11. Kb1 Bg7 12.
Be2 Rc8
{ 12...Qc7  is a bit more flexible as the rook can go to b8 later, but both moves are fine. }
13. Nb3 Qc7
{ Black achieves the dream setup while White is struggling to come up with a plan. }
14. h4 Ne5 { The knight is heading to c4. } 15. Qd4
{ A dubious square for the queen as she is now x-rayed by the g7-bishop   15.Bd4  is more logical but after  15...O-O  16.Qe3  Rfe8!?   @@StartBracket@@  16...Nc4  17.Bxc4  bxc4  18.Nd2  e5  19.Bb6⩲  @@EndBracket@@   @@StartBracket@@  16...Ned7!?  @@EndBracket@@  17.Rhe1  e6!  The position remains complex. White ran out of useful moves, and Black will slowly take over the game. }
15... Nc4 { Black executes the key plan. } 16. Bxc4 bxc4 17. Nc1 Rb8
{ Now it's clear that the rook belongs on the b-file.  This is where our theory ends in the course! }
18. N1e2 { 18.Qb6?  Qxb6  19.Bxb6  Bxe4-+ } 18... O-O
{ Finally Black castles at the most opportune moment. The threat of ...Nxe4 is quite real! }
19. Qd2 Bxe4
{ The killer tactic! Black blasts open the b-file and the h8-a1 diagonal for an unstoppable attack. }
20. fxe4 Nxe4 21. Nxe4
{ 21.Qe1  Qa5!  22.Kc1  Rxb2!  leads to a beautiful finish  23.Kxb2  Rb8+  24.Ka2  Bxc3  25.Nxc3  Nxc3+  26.Ka1  Qxa3 }
21... Rxb2+ 22. Kc1 Qb7
{ And White resigned due to unstoppable threats, for example: } 23. N2c3 Rb1+
24. Nxb1 Qb2# *

