[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Stockfish 8 vs. Stockfish 15"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 g6
{ This is the Hyper-Accelerated Dragon move order. Black's idea is to fianchetto the bishop on g7 first, controlling the long diagonal.   Please note that we avoid  2...Nc6  as it allows  3.Bb5  which is known as the Rossolimo Variation, which leads to totally different types of positions. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6
{ This is my recommended way to play this opening as by attacking the e4-pawn we sidestep the Maroczy Bind  4...Nc6  4.c4  . }
5. Nc3 Nc6 6. Nxc6 dxc6 7. Qxd8+ Kxd8 8. Bc4 Ke8 9. a4 e5 10. Bg5
{ To illustrate that Black can even play for a win in this endgame, I ran a match between Stockfish 8 and Stockfish 15. This game really impressed me how SF15 outplayed it's younger sister. }
10... Nd7 11. O-O-O f6
{ Black solidifies his center and gets ready to develop the dark-square bishop }
12. Be3 Bc5
{ Remember that the trade of dark-square bishops favors Black in these structures. }
13. Bh6 Bf8 14. Bd2
{ White is feeling ambitious!   14.Be3  of course Black can make a draw with repetition, but even  14...h5!?  with idea ...Bh6 is possible here }
14... Nc5 15. Be3 h5 { Black is thinking about ...Bh6 and ...h4 ideas } 16. b3
h4 { Grabbing more space } 17. Rd2 Ne6 18. Rhd1 Bb4
{ now that White has weakened with b3, SF15 happily sets up the pin } 19. Kb2
Ke7
{ We can conclude that Black is quite happy with the resulting endgame. The king is well-placed on e7. Now SF15 will show a masterclass on how to outplay 3200 rated player. }
20. f3 b6 { Black is in no hurry as White has no plan. } 21. Bf2 Rb8 22. Be3 a5
23. Ra1 { A sign that something has gone wrong already! } 23... g5
{ Space grabbing is in order, ...h3 is next } 24. Rh1 h3 25. g3 g4
{ Instructive way to create k-side weaknesses. } 26. Bxe6 Bxe6 27. f4 exf4 28.
Bxf4 Rbd8
{ Black won the bishop pair, but still a long way from winning the game } 29.
Rxd8 Rxd8 30. Be3 Bc5 { An unusual decision based on concrete ideas. } 31. Re1
{ 31.Bxc5+  bxc5  32.Rd1  Rd4!  followed by ...Kd6 and Ke5 activating the king }
31... Bd4 32. Bxd4 Rxd4 33. Kc1 Kd6 34. Nd1 b5
{ Black opens up the 2nd front of attack } 35. axb5 cxb5 36. Re3 Ke5
{ Total domination! } 37. Nf2 Rd8 38. Re2 a4 39. bxa4 bxa4 40. Re3 Ra8 41. Ra3
Kd4 42. Rd3+ Kc4 43. Kb2 f5
{ Black already shows a winning edge of -2, but the game could easily go on for another 30+ moves. I will end here since SF15 won easily. }
*

